ic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"NOTTON","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Notton in Lacock (Wilts) or Notton in Maiden Newton (Dorset), both of which are recorded as  <i>Natton</i> and  <i>Netton</i> in the 13th century. The place-names derive from Old English  <i>nēat</i> ‘cattle’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. There has probably been some confusion with   Noton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Natton","meanings":["English: variant of both   Notton   and   Noton  ."]},{"name":"Noton","meanings":["English: locative name from Notton (WR Yorks), which is recorded as  <i>Notone</i> in 1086 and  <i>Nocton</i> in 1230. The place-name derives from Old English  <i>hnoc</i> ‘wether sheep’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. There has probably been some confusion with   Notton  , and perhaps also with   Knutton   and   Nocton  ."]}]},{"name":"Cristiana","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin.  See  <b>Christina</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Christina","meanings":["Simplified form of Latin <i>Christiana</i>, feminine form of <i>Christianus</i> (  see  Christian  ), or a Latinized form of Middle English <i>Christin</i> ‘Christian’ (Old English <i>christen</i>, from Latin)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Cristiana De NOTTON was born about 1257,